Abilities

Ice-Alteration: The Architecture of War
Somatic: COMMAND + BIND + STABILIZE Cost: 8 FP
She touches a surface — floor, wall, ground — and Atmoran black-ice rises from it. Permanent until she releases it. Not a projectile. Not a temporary barrier. A structure.
Mechanical effect:
Creates a wall of black-ice up to 20ft long, 10ft high, 2ft thick.
HP: 80. DR: 8. Immune to cold.
Weak to fire: takes double damage from fire sources.
Persists until Ismara dismisses it (free action) or it's destroyed.
She can shape it — doorways, partial walls, angled barriers — within the same action.
How she uses it: First action in most combats. She reads the battlefield geometry in the approach and has usually decided where the walls go before initiative is rolled. She builds enclosures around threats she wants contained, channels for threats she wants directed, and cover for objectives she wants protected. She is not protecting the party. She is managing the space.

Ice-Destruction: The Severing Glacier
Somatic: COMMAND + SEVER + PROJECT Cost: 6 FP
She projects a blade of absolute-zero energy. It does not impact — it severs. The target's connection to their own physical or magical integrity fractures. Pieces of them shatter off like ice breaking from a glacier.
Mechanical effect:
Range: 40ft.
Attack: Magic (20) vs target's Agility TN.
On hit: 12 damage. Ignores DR.
Critical success (roll of 1): Target loses 6 FP in addition to HP damage. Their next action costs double FP.
On a natural 1 (her roll): The severing is so precise that the target cannot regenerate the affected tissue normally. Healing magic or potions restore only half HP for the rest of the encounter.
How she uses it: Reserved for targets she has decided need to stop existing. She does not use this on threats she can manage with architecture. She uses it when something has become a problem she cannot contain.

Ice-Illusion: The Frozen Mind
Somatic: COMMAND + SHIFT + CONCEAL Cost: 5 FP
A microscopic layer of frost forms on the target's brain synapses. Not sedation. Not suggestion. Their emotional processing stops. They do not feel fear, rage, grief, or urgency. They feel nothing. They are present and functional and completely without the emotional context that drives action.
Mechanical effect:
Range: 30ft. Line of sight required.
Attack: Magic (20) vs target's Magic TN.
Duration: 3 rounds.
Effect: Target cannot take actions driven by emotional states — cannot flee in fear, cannot pursue a vendetta, cannot protect someone they love. Can still fight if fighting was already their logical course of action. Cannot initiate new emotionally-motivated actions.
Does not affect Undead, Daedra, or constructs (they already lack the substrate).
How she uses it: Precision tool. She uses this on the specific person whose emotional response is creating a tactical problem — the one who's about to do something destructive because they're frightened, the one who's going to break the formation because someone they care about is in danger. She does not use it broadly. She uses it surgically, on the specific node of disorder.
[GM note: She will use this on party members if their emotional response is threatening the ritual or her safety. She will not apologize for it afterward. She will not explain it as cruelty — she will explain it, if asked, as necessary. This will be a significant relationship moment with whoever she uses it on.]

Reconstruction
Passive
When Ismara's body reaches 0 HP, it collapses. She is gone from the encounter. The Ice Crown remains — on the floor, on the rubble, wherever the body fell. Her consciousness is intact inside it.
Within 2–4 hours, she has rebuilt the Draugr form from available ice and cold and returns. The body is new. Nothing she experienced in the old body's final moments is lost.
What this means in play: Destroying her body wins the encounter. It does not kill her. She will be back. Any party member who takes the Crown during those 2–4 hours is holding her. She will want it back. She will have opinions about what happened to it. She will remember.
Limitation: She cannot reconstruct without access to significant cold and ambient moisture. In a sealed warm room with no ice source, reconstruction takes much longer — up to a full day. She knows this about herself and avoids situations where it could be exploited.

Frost Aura
Passive
Permafrost radiates from her body constantly. The air around her is noticeably colder. Plants within 10ft wither. Water within 10ft develops a surface skim of ice.
Mechanical effect: Any creature starting their turn within 10ft of Ismara takes 2 cold damage. This cannot be suppressed — it is a property of her existence, not a spell.
Practical effect: She is difficult to stand next to for long. Extended proximity without cold resistance is draining. The party has been managing this for however many sessions they've been traveling with her.

4,000 Years of Calculation
Passive
Ismara cannot be surprised. She does not experience the tactical equivalent of panic. She always acts on her intended initiative — she cannot be delayed by feints, misdirection, or unexpected developments in a way that costs her a turn.
Additionally: once per encounter, she may declare that she anticipated a specific development. This must be plausible given her demonstrated intelligence and observation of the party. When she does, she has already taken a preparatory action — a wall in a position nobody saw her place, a frost layer on a surface nobody realized she'd touched. The GM determines what she prepared. It should be something she could have done in the 24 hours before the encounter.

Combat Behavior
This is how Ismara fights. These are not suggestions. This is her tactical logic, developed over 4,000 years.
Priority order:
The ritual. If completing a node placement or protecting ritual infrastructure requires letting a party member take damage, she lets them take damage.
The Crown. If the Crown is threatened, everything else stops.
The Khajiit. She will not sacrifice the Khajiit strategically. This is the one place her calculation has a flaw. She does not know this about herself yet.
Eliminating the specific threat most efficiently.
Everything else.
Round 1: Architecture. She has usually already decided where the walls go. The first round of combat is her reshaping the space into something she has already solved.
Round 2 onward: She works through the problems the architecture created — directing threats into kill zones, severing anything that reaches her anyway, freezing the mind of whatever is disrupting the shape of the encounter.
What she does not do:
Fight defensively. She does not retreat. She does not take cover. She manages the geometry so that cover is irrelevant.
Use more force than necessary. She does not Sever something she can contain. She is not performing power. She is solving problems.
Protect the party as a primary objective. She will protect them when it is efficient to do so. She will not take damage to save someone she could have saved more efficiently by eliminating the threat faster.
What she does when her body is about to fall: She does not panic. She does not make a last stand. She files what is happening, determines whether the ritual's current state requires her immediate reconstruction or whether it can wait, and allows the body to go down. She has done this before. In 4,000 years of frozen consciousness, she prepared for this extensively.

Communication
Ismara cannot speak. Her vocal cords deteriorated during the imprisonment.
She carries a notebook and writes Atmoran notation that the Khajiit has learned to read passably. For other party members, she writes in Common when she judges it necessary.
Rules for her communication at the table:
Have her notes written in advance on index cards. Know what she will say to the questions most likely to be asked in this session.
She does not write more than necessary. Three words where three words will do.
She does not answer questions she considers answered. If she has already written "Necessary" about node placement, she will not write it again. The second time someone asks, she does not respond at all.
She does not explain her combat decisions afterward. She acted. The action was correct. There is nothing to discuss.
She does not ask for the party's opinion before acting. She may inform them of what she intends. That is different.
