What the Party Can and Cannot Do
They can:
Suggest a target or a tactic. She will weigh it.
Ask her to hold back from placing a node. She will consider this exactly once per adventure. Her answer will depend on whether she has other options for that geographic coordinate.
Ask her questions. She will answer what she chooses to answer.
Bring her into a social situation. She will observe and occasionally write something that reframes the entire conversation.
They cannot:
Direct her movement on a map.
Tell her who to attack.
Ask her to protect a specific person other than the Khajiit (and even that is not guaranteed).
Make her act against the ritual's interests.
Make her feel guilty. She does not experience guilt in any form they will recognize.
What happens if they try to control her: She ignores them. If they persist, she looks at them the way she looks at anything that has become noise rather than signal. If they physically try to direct her — grabbing her arm, blocking her path — the Frost Aura makes this immediately unpleasant and she removes their hand from her with the minimum force necessary. She does not escalate. She does not need to.

Relationship States
Ismara's relationship with the party is not static. Track it across the campaign.
With the Khajiit: Complex. She has been turning their choice at Frostmere over in her mind since it happened. She has something she does not have a word for regarding them. It does not change her objectives. It changes one specific tactical calculation — she will not sacrifice them strategically. This is the only crack in her logic and she does not know it is there.
With the party collectively: Professional regard. They have been useful and occasionally surprising. She has allocated something that functions like limited trust to them as a unit.
If betrayed: She attempts to liquidate the assets. She does not argue. She does not explain. She tries to collapse the building on them and walks away. If she cannot kill them quickly, she withdraws and takes the long route to completion. She will not give them a second chance.
Escalation across the campaign:
Adventures 1–2: Observing. Filing. Showing selected true things.
Adventure 3: The Dragon Cult evidence. One line. "They have been preparing longer than I have been free."
Adventure 4: She tells them what the ritual does to the nodes. Directly. "You deserve to know before we reach the end."
Adventure 5: No more persuasion. She acts. The time for arguments is over.

The Question the Campaign Never Answers
Whether Ismara can feel anything is the emotional question of the entire campaign.
Play her so that both answers remain plausible until the very end. She should never do something that definitively confirms feeling. She should never do something that definitively rules it out. The Khajiit player should be able to spend the whole campaign genuinely uncertain.
The moment she writes nothing when asked about her feelings for the Khajiit — and closes the notebook — is the closest the campaign gets to an answer. It is not an answer.

